It's so much fun watching you and the other girls hunt ghosts, become the hunted, interact with each other, get scared. It better realizes the original premise, because it doesn't have to deal with the unfortunate roadblock of the real-life shows that ghosts actually don't and can't exist. 

They try and edit around it and get creative, but in a game, you can just have the thing be real and kill people. Way more engaging.

author: @Hwyadylaw

text: ¬†@Hwyadylaw¬† I understand, but if dont understand what they say at all, you cant learn. I turn them on occasionally if i am new to a series, so i can learn to understand the mumbling of some characters.
author: @Codiac300

text:
¬†@Hwyadylaw¬† I'm fluent now and I don't need subs at all, but I'd suggest starting with subs in English if possible, if not in your language, then gradually switch to English subs and finally turning them off. In the end, it depends on the person but forcing stuff and not enjoying the stuff you're watching because you don't understand will pretty much lead to discouragement and then dropping the idea of learning the language so I rather do things gradually, and It worked for me so... there's that.
And if this person watches streams occasionally while watching movies with subs, they might improve because they might grasp things but because they watched others with subtitles before.
Personally, I'd also recommend watching subbed clips, Ted Talks, YouTubers too because people talk on them differently, I improved a lot when I started watching Ted Talks and informative YouTubers of my field.
author: @Vintagestep

text:
¬†@Vintagestep¬† 
Of course watching with subtitles is better than not watching at all. If you can understand even 40% without subtitles, it's worth disabling them. What you're really learning are the things you understand partially or need to think about to understand. The goal of practice is to maximise how much you have to think or try to remember, not maximise how much you understand immediately.
